{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512699"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:59:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:59:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11938"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11938"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.12,0.07,0.08,0.68]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4534"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104529"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4534"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11938"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86856"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2632"},{"type":"tags","id":"3356"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"4339"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43879"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104529","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104529"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of yellowish discoloration of her eyes. She reports similar episodes occurring intermittently since her early twenties, typically lasting two to four days and coinciding with periods of stress or reduced food intake. She mentions occasional abdominal cramping and bloating associated with heavy meals. She denies nausea, dark urine, pale stools, pruritus, or weight loss. She has recently completed a course of cephalexin for a urinary tract infection. She was treated for iron deficiency anaemia last year when she trialed a vegan diet, and this improved with 3 months of iron supplements.  She takes only a multivitamin now.  There is a strong family history of breast and ovarian cancer in her maternal aunty, maternal grandmother and maternal great aunt.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Her BMI is 31 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Scleral icterus is noted. Her abdomen is soft and non-tender, with no organomegaly. There are no stigmata of chronic liver disease. Investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 110 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETotal bilirubin: 52.2 \u00b5mol/L (3.0-20.5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDirect bilirubin: 3.2 \u00b5mol/L (\u0026lt;5.1)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAST: 22 U/L (10-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALT: 25 U/L (7-56)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EALP: 65 U/L (30-120)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELactate dehydrogenase (LDH): 180 U/L (125-220)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaptoglobin: 1.2 g/L (0.3-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Biliary colic","Haemolytic anaemia","Dubin-Johnson syndrome","Crigler-Najjar syndrome","Gilbert syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003EGilbert syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition is characterised by mild, chronic, or recurrent unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia in the absence of liver disease or overt haemolysis. The diagnosis is typically made during young adulthood, and exacerbations often occur during periods of stress, fatigue, or reduced caloric intake, as seen in this case. The benign, self-limited nature of the episodes and the absence of significantly abnormal liver function tests support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrigler-Najjar syndrome type\u003C/strong\u003Es\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003E1 and \u003Cstrong\u003E2\u003C/strong\u003E and Gilbert syndrome are all hereditary forms of unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia that result principally from mutations in \u003Cem\u003EUGT1A1\u003C/em\u003E. In Crigler-Najjar type 1, essentially no functional enzyme activity is present, whereas patients with Crigler-Najjar type 2 have up to 10% of normal and patients with Gilbert syndrome have 10 to 33% of normal activity. Because total UGT1A1 enzymatic activity must be reduced to less than 50% of normal to produce unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia, phenotypic expression of mutations in this enzyme requires either homozygosity or double heterozygosity, and each of these disorders is inherited as an autosomal recessive trait. The mild and intermittent nature of this patient\u0027s symptoms makes Crigler-Najjar syndrome less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDubin-Johnson syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is also a hereditary disorder characterised by conjugated hyperbilirubinaemia. While it can present with intermittent jaundice, the predominantly unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia in this case makes Dubin-Johnson syndrome an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBiliary colic\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with right upper quadrant pain, nausea, and vomiting. While this patient reports occasional abdominal discomfort and has risk factors for gallstones such as being obese and female, her longstanding gastrointestinal symptoms are more typical of irritable bowel syndrome, and biliary colic is usually associated with normal bilirubin levels unless there is biliary obstruction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemolytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia and be triggered by medications including cephalosporins. However, it is typically accompanied by anaemia, elevated LDH, and decreased haptoglobin. While she is mildly anaemic, the normal LDH, and haptoglobin levels in this patient make haemolytic anaemia an unlikely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gilbert syndrome is characterised by mild, chronic, or recurrent unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia in the absence of liver disease or overt haemolysis.","Fasting and stress can exacerbate unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia in Gilbert syndrome."],"references":["Wagner KH, Shiels RG, Lang CA, Seyed Khoei N, Bulmer AC. Diagnostic criteria and contributors to Gilbert\u0027s syndrome. Crit Rev Clin Lab Sci. 2018 Mar;55(2):129-139. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29390925/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86856"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11938"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86856"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T13:13:17+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T13:13:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4534"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104529"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedic